.TH BUNPY-MAN 1 "2026-04-27" "bunpy" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
bunpy-man \- read or install bunpy's bundled manpages
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bunpy man
.I command
.br
.B bunpy man
\-\-install
[\fIdir\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Bunpy ships its own manpages. They live as
.B embed.FS
data baked into the binary, so an install of
.B bunpy
always knows where to find them.
.PP
.B bunpy man
.I command
prints the requested page in raw
.B roff
to standard output. Pipe to
.B man -l -
to render:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ bunpy man run | man -l -
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B bunpy man --install
.RI [ dir ]
copies all bundled pages into
.IR dir/man1/ .
The default
.I dir
is
.IR $HOME/.bunpy/share/man .
.B install.sh
runs this on every install so the user does not need to do it
manually. The Homebrew formula installs the same files via
.B man1.install
during
.BR "brew install" .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B MANPATH
Add
.I $HOME/.bunpy/share/man
to it (or to
.IR /etc/manpaths.d )
so
.B man bunpy
works after a shell-installer install.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bunpy (1),
.BR man (1).
